[2]
Date: 25 Oct 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: OIE [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_41.HTM#Sec13>

Newcastle disease in Turkey
---------------------------
See also: 9 Dec 2005, 11 Nov 2005, 30 Jul 2004, 16 Jul 2004, 9 Jul 2004.
(Date of previous outbreak of Newcastle disease in Turkey reported to the
OIE: October 2005)
Immediate notification report.
Information received on 7 Dec 2005 from Dr Nihat Pakdil, general director
of protection and control, Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Affairs, Ankara:
Report date: 6 Dec 2005.
Reason for immediate notification: re-occurrence of a listed disease or
infection in a country or zone/compartment following a report declaring the
outbreak(s) ended.
Date of 1st confirmation of the event: 16 Nov 2005.
Date of start of the event: 12 Nov 2005.
Clinical disease: yes.
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, postmortem, and laboratory.
Details of outbreak:
1st administrative division: Ankara
Lower administrative division: Polatli
Type of epidemiological unit: village
Name of the location: Gumusyaka
Date of start of the outbreak: 12 Nov 2005
Species: avi
Number of animals in the outbreak
susceptible / cases / deaths / destroyed / slaughtered
140* / 40 / 40 / 100 / 0
*100 hens and 40 turkeys
Diagnosis:
The Central Veterinary Control and Research Institute, Ankara conducted
inoculation into embryonated chicken eggs, hemagglutination test, and
hemagglutination inhibition (HI) test on 16 Nov 2005, all with positive
results. The intracerebral pathogenicity index test conducted on 18 Nov
2005 yielded ICPI = 1.77
Source of outbreak or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive.
Control measures undertaken:
- stamping out;
- quarantine;
- movement control inside the country;
- zoning;
- disinfection of infected premises/establishments.
Other details/comments:
- in the outbreak area, a total of 40 birds died (30 hens and 10 turkeys),
and the remaining 100 birds (70 hens and 30 turkeys) were culled. All
carcasses were buried the same day with lime in 2 pits dug on the farm
premises.
- clinical surveillance has started in the zone.
- biosecurity measures have been increased.
- public awareness is being raised, and training sessions are being conducted.
Final report: no.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[It appears as if the proverbial wires got crossed for these 2 postings.
The 1st was dated 9 Dec 2005 and declares a final report ending the event.
The 2nd report is 2 days earlier, 7 Dec 2005, and indicates a reoccurrence
and new outbreak of the disease. The 2 outbreaks near Bursa (Sea of Marmara
) and Ankara, respectively, are quite distant from each other and probably
represent 2 distinct events. See map:
<http://www.ims.metu.edu.tr/images/turkey%20map.jpg>. - Mod.PC]
